    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-14T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-14T04:00:00-05:00" n="153"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d153">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8767: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Canton</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Linnell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi>
                        </placeName>, [<date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-14T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 14, 1937—5 p.m.</date>]<lb/>[Received July 14—8:38
                        p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Sino-Japanese situation South China. No excitement apparent among people Canton.
                    Kwangtung apparently satisfied to follow Chiang Kai-shek and accept his
                    decision. Many conflicting rumors circulating. General Yu Han Mou now inspecting
                    troops border Fukien. He was expected to proceed thence to Lursan but statement
                    is made that he will now return to Canton. Generals Li and Pai, Kwangsi, have
                    telegraphed to Chiang Kai-shek, to Minister and Vice Minister of War, and others
                    assuring support of Kwangsi and urging firm resistance against Japanese
                    Army.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Linnell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
